The offices include kindergarten, architects understood
The Avriopoint administration building in Brno is the new seat of Arch.Designer.
No one would expect to hide a mini-nursery with everything that comes with it - coloured walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys, and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Designer employees can visit it.
The design-architectural company Arch.Design, from which studios came a number of important Brno buildings, has been counting on the space for its company mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly at the age of Babyboom, and it cared about women designers and architects being able to get back to work quickly.
Together with the possibility of shortened time, the kindergarten is a benefit offered by Arch.Design to its employees under the social programme.
Thus, builders and architects can combine demanding jobs with childcare.
The mini-school was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (grant of CZK 2.8m) they could purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design has an obligation to operate a mini-kindergarten at its own expense for 3 years.
It took one year to prepare the project, and Economy Rating helped significantly with the subsidy application.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the nurse and the teacher of the school take care of the children all day, so children can go to the school without age restrictions, yet they are mostly older than 3 years of age.
Since this is a "mini-school," only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more children can be replaced during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of standing in the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the mini-kindergarten is comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation to school benches, and English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their children at any time, and stress situations with delayed picking up children from nurseries away from their parents' workplaces fall out.
So parents use working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal relationship between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design has thus joined Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are friendly to the family and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors from Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
From the locals, the house earned its organic shape by calling it the House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, shards and mosaics, facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all typical of Antoni Gaudí's Art Nouveau.
The front of the house starts with dream lines, soft colors and texture resembling nature and animals.
You can see the geometry, the rhythm, and the precise order of thought.
At night the whole facade of houses sounds even more dramatic, it is lit so that the impression of the gloss of colors is even more enhanced.
The guilt and twisting of shapes also occurs in the interior.
The wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, pegs and bars.
The house Batlló, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the house from the architect Emilio Sal Cortes in 1877.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, a wealthy industrialist Joseph Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand-new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper rebuilding.
But Antoni Gaudí did not design Casa Batlló's house of business.
The architect Joseph Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his designer board that decorations were created for the property owner's representative apartment as well as the use of mosaics on the facade.
Many other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the design of Casa Batlló started with the successful cooperation of Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá and Park Güell, in which there are other Gaudí works.
From the locals, soon after completion, the house earned its organic shape by the nickname "House of Bones."
Others began to call it "the yawning house" because of the specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs include other sculptures elements of the building.
Gaudí designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five degree slope.
In the creation of Gaudí he absolutely disrespected the construction regulations at the time and did not let them bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, although he obtained a building permit from the city, the figures on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when the construction was completed, the city council was threatened by the result and asked for redress.
The councilman, for example, was upset that the building also interfered with the public pavement.
On the contrary, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully acquired) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building only 15 days after the city's call.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a lounge and on the third floor a bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house crosses the stairwell, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the lounge door and the larger society can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the Gaudí house also received an unconventional roof and two extra floors.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which is lined with inner courtyard, and skylights, is also impressive.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
The House of Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most luxurious apartment made available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150-year anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They remained on the tour because they found it to be a very advantageous business and, moreover, extended the tour to common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is certainly not negligible, it amounts to EUR 16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes have a 20% discount.
The sum significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you must quickly make friends with one of the residents of the tenement and visit it directly at home.
