People's tracking machines want more and more parents, so they want to keep their kids safe.
Fear for your own child brings more and more people to the idea of GPS babysitting.
The system originally created for the search for cars can also monitor the movement of people and thus help, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of 9-year-old Anna Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
A lot of people were terrified of the missing Annie case and started looking for ways to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment on the Czech market.
"I admit that in a certain case, such devices may be misused, for example, if they are put in a bag by someone who doesn't know, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Usually customers actually buy it for security reasons," added Pilin.
According to him, the child should always know for what purpose the "box" is used and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Boček points out that if a child doesn't want to wear anything like this, they'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be in control."
"Great expectations were raised earlier with parents by cell phones, but they can be turned off just like these tracking devices," says Bočková.
According to it, it is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the kidnapping is concerned, the perpetrator will virtually always ensure that the child has no electronics to reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When the tracking devices start to expand, they'll be looking for them, too, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it admits that a similar device may help in the event of sudden infestation by a pedophile.
According to Robert Czech from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and persons, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after the attack, its presence can help.
"The device may be adjusted to periodically send the position after a certain period of time. '
"Should damage occur, at least the last position of the person concerned shall be available. ';
"Expensive devices have also built-in tilting meters, so even if a man just slipped and remained still, the machine will immediately send out a warning with a position indication," says Czech Republic.
According to him, smart mobile phones with navigation can also carry a similar service, where you can upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to pendants the size of a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
That's always the risk of losing them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, therefore, a device that looks like a standard digital watch is now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that any aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or recognize them after a while and it can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device develops into bracelets or necklaces, they will still use the same technology used to guard cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning (which uses conventional autonavigation) and mobile phone functions that report the current position of the car.
