Longer index finger than ring finger indicates lower cancer risk
Men who have a forefinger longer than a ring finger are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by a British cancer magazine.
It could be related to the levels of male testosterone hormone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60," said the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, Professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, has been provided by Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients with colleagues in Britain, and simultaneously over 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had a index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They paid for the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those who had a index finger longer than a ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, for men up to the age of 60, even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - appears to reflect the various levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone matches a longer index finger.
Early research has shown that testosterone is the one that promotes growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences Professor Václav Paches for ČTK said that he knew about this study very well, but he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "fully proven."
