Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private business.
Criminal activity raises more concerns than unemployment.
And many regions consider Brazil more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current survey of Latinobarómetro, which took place in 18 countries and came out exclusively in The Economist magazine.
As the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
In this year's survey, which took place in September and early October, two related things dominate.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has been on average 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% in that year.
It also grew in Mexico, where economics recovered after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of the questions asked in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced democrats, which withdraws the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region have expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, this is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (graph 3).
Around 34% said that they trusted the Assembly in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same figures as last year, but there was a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
The support was created during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the ratio of Latinos living in poverty only slightly increased in 2009 and fell back to 32% this year.)
However, the mood varies in a wide range from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its resigning President Luiz Inácia Lula da Silva are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and the state of violent crime deteriorated.
Only the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Around 31% say that either they or their close relatives became victims of crime last year, but this is a decrease compared to the figure 38% of last year and is also the lowest number since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in increasing support for private business and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say that private business is necessary for development, this percentage has increased from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage has increased from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of the respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% support private business there), although their left-wing President Hugo Chávez expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is a country that has a leading position in the area, as 19% of respondents mentioned (compared to 18% of last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country of respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
