The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines in production plants around the world, in power plants and for high precision devices.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thereby avoiding unnecessary errors and expenditure.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the Siemens industrial division, explains that the use of this software device allowed the Red Bull team to perform "within a few hours, in almost real time" modifications and improvements that will otherwise be detected during races and tests.
Russwurm says that in 1992 they employed on average 10 technicians who were able to perform a maximum of three or four improvements in one period.
The Red Bull team is today working on 180 young highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology who analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is capable of analysing and improving all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles, except for an engine for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features shall be modified.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using laser and high technology autoclaves.
The only limit on this technical option is $40 million, which represents the maximum that each Formula 1 team can spend for each period of time to improve its competitiveness.
