Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin has decided to maintain the euro, but has set conditions for the whole Union.
The tensions in the markets provoked a dual government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, from tax reductions for small and medium-sized enterprises, to the regulation of private intermediation agencies, to the abolition of 426 euros for unemployed people, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA (Spanish airports and air traffic control - note), the airport manager Barajas and El Prat, and 30% of the state lottery.
Vice-President Elena Salgado, supported by former Prime Minister Felipe González, has, on the other hand, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility for unleashing the current crisis.
How do you interpret these movements?
Let us be clear in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, this is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is supposed to be, which comes across the idea of adhering to old traditions, which is held by a large proportion of other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro area that would include Germany, but also Austria or the Netherlands, for example, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the mark - although it may now appear to be Scifi, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to German proposals, is to rework the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary rigour, fines for guilty states, possible deferral of payments for some of them, and to extend the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time now, so there is no room for spin now.
First, when the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission fueled deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from doing so from 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany thought was right (fiscal rigour and public finance stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel was painfully delaying the decision to rescue Greece.
It was already the subject of strong criticism at the time, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has once again appeared with a clear opinion, demanding to reform the European Union's conventions in order to enable the rescue of a Member State while at the same time obliging private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as being anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although somewhat mitigated, has been approved, and we should monitor the Union's reform process over the coming months, which should allow for these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has set a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures must now be taken, with which it seems to disagree too much, from this date, the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will represent the birth of a new currency zone in which rule-breakers are severely sanctioned and can be forced to announce deferral, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we need to take a strict path of growth with an increase in savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
Another option based on claims and construction, with huge balance of payments gaps, which it ruled in the years of Spain's boom, is simply not to be tolerated.
The offer is clear.
And we would have made a mistake if we didn't understand.
This is not just a reopening of the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they're asking us to do is much harder.
And worst of all, under these conditions, we could be wrong ourselves.
