The United States is amending the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the services centres for visa applicants before the interview at the Consultative Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the visa process will change at the United States Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Service Centres (ASC in short) before the interview at the Consultative Department.
The ASC staff shall remove the applicant's biometric information and be evaluated by the Consultative Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer need to pay a fee for the appointment, the second for processing the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary staff visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Given that biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who require a second interview with the Consultative Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the service of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following website: http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs.html
