World plan for lighting renewal
Yesterday, in Cancún, the UN proposed a plan to restore domestic lighting, lighting of shops and industrial areas in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse effect reduction (GES), which corresponds to almost one third of the next restriction to be achieved to stabilise the planet's climate from now to 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implement commitments to reduce on the part of industrialised countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if we replace hot bulbs that monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market with fluo-compact or, even better, electric-luminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emissions on a planet created for lighting would be cut off.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of the fleet emissions on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, were involved in voluntary reduction plans that should allow the global emissions of GES to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance in order to achieve a stabilization of climate heating to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020, so that it can be excluded that it will not get out of control.
In heated filament lamps 95% of energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluoro-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new bulbs with DEL, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluo-compact bulbs can withstand an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
New bulbs with DEL, one that was introduced this week into Philips' production - this company allegedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, which gives us an idea of possible savings with a substitution plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluoro-compact filament lamps because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, unless producers set up collection centres.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluoro-compact bulb, but rather a thermal coal-fired power plant that emits many mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
Only in the United States do these centers put 25 000 tons of mercury into circulation every year.
The report also gives in detail the profits each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 heat plants, whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
