The rule that secret documents can only consist of reports already known is crucial in the dynamics of secret services, not just in this century.
When you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric literature, you will see that every work repeats (about Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, Templars or Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of the occult texts does not like to seek new information (he does not know where to find reports of non-existent ones), but because those who are devoted to the occult believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have learned before.
That's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
