Information with high secrecy about Berlusconi that the US Embassy sent to the State Department was the same information Newsweek published a week before.
Then why is there so much fuss about the discovery of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since the heads of state can make phone calls or fly on a plane to a joint dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have transformed into a spy center.
Any spectator watching movies about an investigation knows very well that it seems to be seemingly ignored out of self-interest.
However, the fact that this is repeated in public defies the duty of hypocrisy and throws a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most strictly classified information from the most powerful country in the world is a hard strike, not a considerable one, for the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victim and his "executor."
But let's go from here to the deep truth about what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, it was possible to embrace all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every move of his people.
Orvell's prophecy has been proven since the possibility of controlling every move through a phone, every transaction made, a visited hotel, a used highway, and so on, the citizen became the ultimate victim of a wreath of power.
