Climate: how France hacked its financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (fast start or early start) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks were exposed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries have committed to providing $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion for three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (that is, EUR 420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: a report specifying the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued at its true value: an advanced country and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same, with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, leading it to the right path to keep its promise of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional 'to ensure that the increased burden is realised without damaging Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or with terms at the level of public aid for development.
By contrast, France considers that the funding of "all new projects' in 2010 is" new and additional '.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, France's total aid to developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease), with a view to complying with its commitment to funding "new and additional '...
Another decisive element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 borrowed equals €1 donated.
Clearly, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be evidenced for some investments that are profitable (often projects linked to reducing emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as equivalent to one euro that we give..., we should not see it as a result of our commitments, but as a loan price for the creditor country (i.e. interest rate equivalent).
But France can only give the following reasons: "it respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million, making it a 91,5% loan (EUR 389,8 million) and 8,5% donation (EUR 36,1 million) - see the EU document so that you can verify it yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes use of a loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% from here, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) comply with their obligations with 100% of the donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to the satisfaction of its promise, France gives only 10 centimeters and considers this effort comparable.
What a nice trick!
To summarise, in its "fast start" financing, France operates with double-deceivance: on the one hand, with the development of the stock in time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it only spends EUR 36.1 million, it can convince that it is spending EUR 420 million "new and additional" in relation to its promises.
Manipulating the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and to negotiate because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The early financing chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the findings from this first year of early financing.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and justice towards the other countries of the European Union.
But, above all, France should prevent discussions about deposits in long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the issue of 'additional' or the way in which loans are accounted for.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone puts hope in the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will be coming to Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional" and use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
